  "text": "The patient lies in a supine vertical position, with his shoulders slightly higher than his pelvic position. The practitioner holds the patient's arm at the wrist, abducting it to an overhead position and external rotating it to 90 . Subsequently, the practitioner pushes the humeral head into a superior and lateral direction (Fig. 2) . [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] Traditionally this technique is performed without traction, but it can be modified by applying traction. In a self-reduction technique described by Dudkiewicz the patient abduces and externally rotates his affected arm with his other arm and pushes the humeral head himself in superior and lateral position. [CITATION_3] ",
